### `createRegExp`:
```typescript
export function createRegExp(searchString: string, isRegex: boolean, options: RegExpOptions = {}): RegExp {
    if (!searchString) {
        throw new Error('Cannot create regex from empty string');
    }
    if (!isRegex) {
        searchString = escapeRegExpCharacters(searchString);
    }
    if (options.wholeWord) {
        if (!/\B/.test(searchString.charAt(0))) {
            searchString = '\\b' + searchString;
        }
        if (!/\B/.test(searchString.charAt(searchString.length - 1))) {
            searchString = searchString + '\\b';
        }
    }
    let modifiers = '';
    if (options.global) {
        modifiers += 'g';
    }
    if (!options.matchCase) {
        modifiers += 'i';
    }
    if (options.multiline) {
        modifiers += 'm';
    }
    if (options.unicode) {
        modifiers += 'u';
    }

    return new RegExp(searchString, modifiers);
}
```

Key issue: `if (!options.matchCase)` — this is INVERTED. The `matchCase` option means "should the match be case-sensitive". When `matchCase` is true (case-sensitive search), we should NOT add the 'i' flag. When `matchCase` is false (case-insensitive search), we SHOULD add the 'i' flag.

So the logic should be:
- `if (!options.matchCase)` → add 'i' flag → case-insensitive when matchCase is false ✓

